# Crime and Punishment - cleaned - Part 1

# — Is it so, Dunia?

---

to have, not to: “Kill dogs if you are not satisfied!” – He laughed.
— Is it so, Dunia?

— No, it is not so, – Dunia replied firmly.

— Bah! and you too… with intentions!.. – he muttered, looking at her
almost with hatred and smiling mockingly. – I should have realized this… Well, commendable; it is better for you… and you will reach such a boundary that you will not cross it – you will be unhappy, and if you cross it – maybe even unhappier… However, all this is nonsense! – he added irritably, annoyed at his involuntary fascination. – I only wanted to say that you, mother, I ask for forgiveness, – he concluded abruptly and distinctly.

— It’s all over, Rodion, I am sure, everything you do, everything is perfect! – said the delighted mother.

— Do not be sure, – he replied, twisting his mouth into a smile. There followed
silence. Something was tense in all this conversation, in the silence and in the reconciliation, and in the forgiveness, and everyone felt it.

“Indeed, they are afraid of me,” – he thought to himself, glancing at his mother and sister with contempt. Pulcheria Alexandrovna, indeed, the more she remained silent, the more timid she became.

“Remotely, it seems they loved them so,” – flashed through his mind.

— You know, Rodion, Marfa Petrovna died! – suddenly exclaimed Pulcheria Alexandrovna.

— What is Marfa Petrovna?

— Oh, my God, that Marfa Petrovna, Svidrigailov! I have written so much about her to you.

— A-a-a, yes, I remember… So she died? Ah, really? — suddenly
he started, as if waking up. — Did she really die? Why?

— Imagine, suddenly! — Pulcheria Alexandrovna hurried, encouraged by his curiosity, — and just at that very moment,
when I sent you that letter then, on that very day! Imagine, this
horrible man seemed to be the cause of her death. They say he beat her terribly!

— Do they live like that? — he asked his sister.

— No, on the contrary. He was always very patient with her, even polite, even too lenient towards her character for many cases… for seven years… Somehow he suddenly lost his patience.

— So he’s not so horrible at all, if he stuck with her for seven years? You,
Duneyka, you seem to be justifying him?

— No, no, that’s a horrible man! I can’t imagine anything more horrible, — Dunya almost shuddered, furrowed her brows and pondered.

— It happened to them in the morning, — she continued in a hurry, — After that she immediately ordered the horses to be saddled, so that they would go to the city immediately after lunch, because she always went to the city in such cases; they say she ate lunch with a great appetite…

— Was she beaten?

— … She, in fact, always had that… habit, and as soon as she had lunch, she immediately set off to the bathhouse… You see, she was treated with bathing; they have a cold key there, and she bathed in it regularly every day, and as soon as she entered the water, a blow!

— Still! — said Zosimow.

— And he beat her badly?

— It’s the same, — responded Dunya.

— Hmm! As for you, mother, to tell about such a sorrow, — he said irritably and almost unintentionally.

— Oh, my friend, I didn’t know what to talk about, — burst out Pulcheria Alexandrovna.

— What are you afraid of, or what? — he said with a twisted smile.

— That’s really true, — said Dunya, looking sternly at her brother. — Mother, even when she stepped on the staircase, she crossed herself in fear.

His face twitched as if from a spasm.

— Oh, Dunya! Please don’t be angry, Rodia… Why, Dunya! — spoke up Pulcheria Alexandrovna in distress, — it’s me, truly, I was riding here, the whole way I dreamed of it, in the carriage: how we would see each other, how we would tell each other everything… and she was so happy she hadn’t seen a road! What am I? I am happy now… In vain, Dunya! I am only happy that I see you, Rodia…

— Enough, mother, — he mumbled with embarrassment, not looking at her and squeezing her hand, — we’ll have time to talk!

Saying this, he suddenly blushed and paled: another recent terrible sensation passed through him like a dead chill; suddenly it became completely clear and understandable to him that he had just said a terrible lie, that he would never again have time to talk, but already about nothing more, never and with anyone, he could not now speak. The impression of this agonizing

He thought about this so intensely that he, for a moment, almost completely forgot himself, got up from the place and, not looking at anyone, walked out of the room.

— What are you doing? — shouted Razumikhin, grabbing him by the hand.

He sat down again and began to look around in silence; everyone was looking at him with bewilderment.

— What are you all so boring? — he suddenly exclaimed, completely unexpectedly, — Say something! What’s the point of sitting like this? Just speak! Let’s talk… Gathered and silent… Just something!

— Thank God! I was thinking that something from yesterday was starting with him, — said Pulcheria Alexandrovna, crossing herself, — What are you, Rodion? — asked Avdotya Romanovna doubtfully.

— I just remembered one thing, — he replied and suddenly laughed.

— Well, if one thing, then that’s good! Otherwise, I myself would have thought… — mumbled Zosim, getting up from the sofa. — I must go, however; I may come back, perhaps… if I catch him…

He said goodbye and left.

— What a wonderful man! — observed Pulcheria Alexandrovna.

— Yes, wonderful, excellent, educated, intelligent… — suddenly spoke Raskolnikov in some unexpected haste and with such an extraordinary animation, — I don’t remember where I met him before… to the point of illness… Seems, somewhere I met him… And this one is also a good man! — he nodded at Razumikhin, — Do you like him, Dunya? — he asked her and suddenly laughed, unknown to what.

— Very much, — answered Dunya.

— Ugh, you are… a pig! — said Razumikhin, extremely confused and red, and got up from the chair. Pulcheria Alexandrovna smiled slightly, and Raskolnikov loudly laughed.

— Where are you?

— Me too… I need to.

— You absolutely don’t need to, stay! Zosimov has left, and you need to too. Don’t go… And what time is it? Is it twelve? What lovely watches you have, Dunya!

— What are you both so silent about? It’s only me and I’m talking!..

— It’s a gift from Martha Petrovna, — Dunya replied.

— And quite large, — Pulcheria Alexandrovna added.

— Oh my! What big ones, almost not ladies’ watches.

— I love such ones, — Dunya said.

— It seems, it’s not a groom’s gift, — Razumikhin thought and, for some reason, was delighted.

— I was thinking it was a gift from Luzhin, — Raskolnikov remarked.

— No, he hasn’t given Duneyochka anything yet.

— Oh my! Do you remember, mother, I was in love and wanted to marry, — he suddenly said, looking at his mother, stunned by the unexpected turn and tone with which he spoke about it, — Ah, my friend, yes! — Pulcheria Alexandrovna glanced at Dunya and Razumikhin.

— Hmm! Yes! What shall I tell you? I don’t even remember much. She was such a sick girl, — he continued, as if suddenly thinking again and looking down, — very sickly; she loved to give to the poor, and she dreamed of the monastery, and she cried when I told her about it; yes, yes… I remember… I remember very well. Such a silly girl… with herself. I don’t know for what I was attached to her, it seems because she was always sick… If she were still limping or hunchbacked, I would probably have loved her even more… (He smiled thoughtfully.) — There’s some springtime nonsense going on here…

— No, there’s more than just springtime nonsense here, — Duneyochka said with enthusiasm.

He looked intently and with tension at his sister, but did not hear or even understand her words. Then, in deep thoughtfulness, he rose, approached his mother, kissed her, returned to his place and sat down.

“You still love her!” Pulcheria Alexandrovna said, moved.

“Her? Now? Ah yes… you’re talking about her! No. It’s all now exactly in that world… and so long ago. And besides, everything that’s happening around isn’t exactly here.”

He looked at them attentively.

“Here are you… I’m looking at you from a thousand versts away…  And who knows why we’re talking about this! And what’s the point of questioning?” he added, with annoyance and fell silent, biting his nails and again pondering.

“What a gloomy apartment you have, Rodya, it’s like a coffin,” Pulcheria Alexandrovna suddenly said, interrupting the gloomy silence, “I’m sure you became half as melancholy as the apartment.”

“Apartment?,” he answered distractedly. “Yes, the apartment contributed… I was thinking about that too… And if you only knew what strange thought you just said, mother,” he added suddenly, strangely smiling.

Just a little longer, and this society, these relatives, after three years of separation, this kindred tone of conversation with the complete impossibility of talking about anything, would finally become unbearable for him. However, there was one urgent matter that, one way or another, had to be resolved today, – he had decided this a long time ago, when he woke up. Now he was rejoicing in the matter, like a release.

“Here’s what, Dunya,” he began seriously and dryly, “I, of course, ask you…”

Forgiveness for yesterday, but I consider it my duty to remind you once again that I will not yield from my principal matter. Either me, or Luzhin. Let me be a scoundrel, but you must not. One of us. If you marry Luzhin, I will immediately cease to consider you my sister.

— Rodia, Rodia! But this is all the same as yesterday, — exclaimed Pulcheria Alexandrovna sadly, — and why do you call yourself a scoundrel, I cannot bear this! And yesterday it was the same…

— Brother, — firmly and also dryly replied Dunya, — there is a mistake on your part in all this. I have thought about it overnight and found the mistake. It’s that you, apparently, assume that I am sacrificing myself for someone and for some purpose. It’s not at all like that. I am simply leaving for myself because it is difficult for me; and then, of course, I will be glad if I can be useful to my relatives, but this is not the main motivation…

“She lies!” — he thought to himself, biting his nails in anger. — “A prude! She doesn’t want to admit that she wants to be benevolent! Oh, low characters! They love, just as they hate… Oh, how I… hate them all!”

— In one word, — continued Duneychka, — I am marrying Peter Petrovich, — because I am choosing the lesser of two evils. I intend to honestly fulfill everything he expects of me, and therefore I do not deceive him… Why are you smiling now?

She also flared up, and anger flashed in her eyes.

— Will you fulfill everything? — asked he, sneering venomously.

— To a certain extent. And the manner and form of Peter Petrovich’s courtship showed me immediately what he needed. He, of course, values himself, perhaps too highly, but I hope he values me too… What are you laughing at again?

— And why are you blushing again? You are lying, sister, you are lying deliberately, solely due to one woman’s stubbornness, just to put everything in front of me on your terms… You cannot respect Luzhin: I have seen him and spoken with him. Therefore, you are selling yourself for money, and, consequently, you are acting low, and I am glad that you, at least, can blush!

— It’s not true, I’m not lying!— exclaimed Duneychka, losing all composure, — I will not marry him unless I am convinced that he values me and cherishes me; I will not marry him unless I am firmly convinced that I myself can respect him. Fortunately, I can certainly ascertain this, and even today. Such a marriage is not a deception, as you say! And if you were right, and I were truly to resort to deception—wouldn’t it be cruel of you to speak to me in this way? Why do you demand heroism from me, of which you, perhaps, lack? This is despotism, this is violence! If I harm anyone, it will only be myself… I have never killed anyone!— What are you looking at me like that? What are you looking like, you’ve paled? Rodia, what’s with you? Rodia, darling!

— Oh, my Lord!— exclaimed Pulcheria Alexandrovna.

— No, no… nonsense… nothing!— A little bit of a headache. Not at all…

Fainting… These fainting spells are bothering you!.. Hmm! Yes… what was I trying to do? Yes: in what way are you going to find out today that you can respect him and that he… values it, as you said? You, it seems, said that today? Or did I misunderstand?

— Mother, show brother the letter of Peter Petrovich, — Duneychka said.

Pulcheria Alexandrovna, with trembling hands, passed the letter. He took it with great curiosity. But before unfolding it, he suddenly looked at Duneychka with surprise.

— It’s strange, — he said slowly, as if suddenly struck by a new thought, — what am I fussing about over? What is all this shouting? Go marry whoever you want!

He was speaking as if to himself, but he voiced it aloud and looked at his sister for a while, as if puzzled.

He finally unfolded the letter, still retaining the appearance of some strange surprise; then he slowly and carefully began to read and read it twice. Pulcheria Alexandrovna was in particular anxiety; and everyone was waiting for something special.

— It’s surprising to me, — he began after some reflection and passing the letter to his mother, but not addressing anyone in particular, — since he goes on business, a lawyer, and even his conversation is such… with a flourish, — but how clumsily he writes.

Everyone stirred; they were expecting something different.

— They all write like that too, — Razumikhin remarked abruptly.

— Did you read it?

— Yes.

— We showed you, Rodion, we… advised recently, — began the confused Pulcheria Alexandrovna.

— This is, in fact, judicial style, — Razumikhin interrupted, — judicial papers are still written like this.

— Judicial? Yes, precisely judicial, businesslike… Not really very illiterately, and not really very literary; businesslike!

— Peter Petrovich doesn’t hide the fact that he studied with copper money, and he even boasts that he himself paved the way for himself, — noted Avdotya Romanovna, somewhat offended by her brother’s new tone.

— Well, if he boasts, then it is so, — I don’t contradict. You, sister, seem to be offended that I extracted such a free-spirited observation from the whole letter, and you think that I deliberately talked about such trifles in order to break my head over you with annoyance. On the contrary, as for the style, it came to me one quite unnecessary observation, in the present case. There is one expression: “blame yourselves,” placed very significantly and clearly, and, moreover, there is a threat that he will leave immediately if I come. This threat to leave is just as good as a threat to throw you both away if you are disobedient, and to throw you away now that he has already called to Petersburg. Well, what do you think: can one be offended by Luzhin with such an expression as if he had written (he pointed to Razumikhin), or Zosim, or any of us?

— No, — replied Duneychka, reviving, — I very much understood that it was expressed too naively and that he, perhaps, is just not a master of writing… You rightly reasoned, brother. I didn’t even expect it…

— This is expressed in a judicial manner, and it cannot be written in a judicial manner otherwise, and it turned out to be rougher than he might have wanted. However, I must disappoint you somewhat: there is still one expression in this letter, one slander against my

The account, and quite a base one. I gave money yesterday to the widow, consumptive and deceased, and not “on the pretext of the funeral,” but directly to the funeral, and not into the hands of the daughter—the maiden, as he writes, “of settled behavior” (and whom I saw for the first time in life yesterday), but to the widow. In all this, I see too hasty a desire to defame me and quarrel with you. It is expressed again in a judicial manner, that is, with too obvious a revelation of purpose and with a haste that is quite naive. He is a clever man, but to act wisely—one’s intelligence is not enough. All this paints a man and… I don’t think he will value you much. I am informing you solely for your instruction, because I sincerely wish you well…

Duneyka didn’t answer; her decision had been made quite recently, she was only waiting for the evening.

— So how are you deciding, Rodya? — asked Pulcheria Alexandrovna, even more recently worried by his sudden, new, businesslike tone of speech.

— What is this: “deciding”?

— Yes, well, Peter Petrovich writes that you shouldn’t be with us in the evening and that he will leave… if you come. So how will you… be?

— That’s, of course, not for me to decide, but firstly, for you, if such a demand from Peter Petrovich doesn’t offend you, and secondly, for Dunya, if she doesn’t offend either. And I will do what is best for you—he added dryly.

— Duneyka has already decided, and I quite agree with her—rushed Pulcheria Alexandrovna to insert.

— I am asking you, Rodya, earnestly asking you to be with us at this date—said Dunya, — will you come?

— I will come.

— I also ask you to be with us at eight o’clock—she turned to
Razumikhin. — Mother, I am also inviting them.

— Excellent, Dunyochka. Well, as you have decided—Pukhleiya Alexandrovna added—so let it be. And it is easier for me; I don’t like to pretend and lie; let us speak the whole truth… Are you angry, or are you not angry now, Peter Petrovich!

  

At that moment the door opened quietly, and one girl entered the room, glancing around shyly. Everyone turned to her with surprise and curiosity. Raskolnikov did not recognize her at first glance. It was Sofya Semenovna Marmeladova. He had seen her for the first time yesterday, but at such a moment, in such a situation and in such a costume, that it was reflected in his memory as a completely different face. Now she was a modestly and even poorly dressed girl, very young, almost like a child, with a modest and proper manner, with a clear, but as if slightly frightened face. She was wearing a very simple home dress, and on her head was an old, unchanged hat; only in her hands she had, as yesterday, an umbrella. Seeing the unexpectedly full room of people, she did not blush, but completely lost herself, became frightened like a small child, and even made a movement to step back.

— Ah… is it you?…—Raskolnikov said in extraordinary surprise and suddenly became embarrassed himself.

It immediately occurred to him that his mother and sister had vaguely, through Luzhin’s letter, known about a certain girl with “pronounced” behavior. Now he was only protesting against Luzhin’s slander and mentioning that he had seen this girl for the first time

Once, and suddenly she entered herself. He also remembered that he had not protested at all against the expression: “pronounced behavior.” All of this was unclear and instantly slipped into his head. But, looking more closely, he suddenly saw that this diminished creature had already been so diminished that he suddenly felt sorry for it. When she had been about to make a movement to run away from fear, – in him something like turned over.

“I did not expect you at all,” he hastened, stopping her with his gaze. “Please, make the courtesy, sit down. You, surely, are from Ekaterina Ivanovna. Allow, not here, sit here…”

When Sonya Razumikhin, sitting on one of the three chairs of Raskolnikov, now standing by the door, leaned forward to let her in. Initially, Raskolnikov had pointed out to her a place in the corner of the sofa where Zosimov was sitting, but, remembering that this sofa was too familiar a place and served him as a bed, he hastened to point out to her the chair of Razumikhin.

“Sit here,” he said to Razumikhin, seating him in the corner where Zosimov was sitting.

Sonya sat down, trembling slightly from fear, and timidly looked at both ladies. It was visible that she herself did not understand how she could sit next to them. Realizing this, she had been so frightened that she suddenly got up again and, in complete confusion, turned to Raskolnikov.

“I… I… I came for one minute, forgive me for disturbing you,” she began to speak, stammering. “I am from Ekaterina Ivanovna, and there was no one to send her…” Ekaterina Ivanovna had ordered him to be at the funeral service tomorrow, in the morning… for lunch… at the Mitrofanievsky, and then with us… at the

ней… откушать… Честь ей сделать… Она велела просить.

Соня запнулась и замолчала.

— Постараюсь непременно… непременно, — отвечал Раскольников, привстав
тоже и тоже запинаясь и не договаривая… — Сделайте одолжение, садитесь, -
сказал он вдруг, — мне надо с вами поговорить. Пожалуйста, — вы, может быть,
торопитесь, — сделайте одолжение, подарите мне две минуты…

— Is that today?

— She is asking you to pay your respects at the funeral service in the church tomorrow, and then to arrive at her place for the memorial service.

— Is she holding a memorial service?

— Yes-yes, a snack; she really asked you to thank you for helping us yesterday… without you, we wouldn’t have been able to bury him at all. — And her lips and chin twitched suddenly, but she hardened herself and held it back, quickly lowering her eyes to the ground again.

While talking, Raskolnikov intently scrutinized her. It was a thin, very thin and pale face, quite irregular, somewhat pointed, with a pointed little nose and chin. It couldn’t even be called pretty, but her blue eyes were so clear, and when they came to life, her expression became so kind and innocent, that it involuntarily attracted attention. There was also one particularly characteristic feature in her face, and in her entire figure: despite her eighteen years, she seemed almost still a child, much younger than her years, almost a child, and this sometimes even appeared amusingly in some of her movements.

— But surely, Katya Ivanovna couldn’t resort to such small means, even a snack is intended…? — Raskolnikov asked, persistently continuing the conversation.

— The coffin will be simple-yes… and everything will be simple, so it will be inexpensive… we recently calculated everything with Katya Ivanovna, so there will be enough to remember… and Katya Ivanovna really wants it to be like that. It can’t be… it’s comfort… she is, as you know…

— I understand, I understand… of course… Why are you looking at my room? Mama says the same thing, that it resembles the coffin.

— You gave us everything yesterday! — Sonya suddenly retorted,
in a strong and quick whisper, suddenly lowering her eyes again. Her lips and
chin trembled again. She had long been struck by the poor circumstances of
Raskolnikov, and now these words suddenly came out on their own.
Silence followed. Dunyasha’s eyes somehow cleared up, and Pulcheria
Alexandrovna even looked at Sonya with a friendly gaze.

— Rodion, — she said, rising, — we, of course, will have dinner together.
Dunyasha, let’s go… And you, Rodion, should go for a walk a little, and then
rest, lie down, and then come sooner… Otherwise, I’m afraid you’ll tire us out…

— Yes, yes, I’ll come, — he replied, rising and hurrying up… — I
have, in fact, business…

— So you will be having dinner separately? — Razumikhin shouted,
looking at Raskolnikov with surprise, — What is this?

— Yes, yes, I’ll come, of course, of course… And you stay for a minute.
Isn’t he needed by you now, mother? Or am I taking him?

— Oh, no, no! And you, Dmitry Prokofievich, will come to dinner,
will you be so kind?

— Please come, — Dunya asked.

Razumikhin parted ways and shone all over. For a moment, everyone
suddenly seemed a little confused.

— Goodbye, Rodion, that is, goodbye; I don’t like to say “goodbye.”
Goodbye, Nastasya… ah, “goodbye” she said again!..

Pulcheria Alexandrovna wanted to bow to Sonya too, but somehow she
didn’t manage, and hurried out of the room.

But Avdotya Romanovna seemed to be waiting in line and, passing
behind her mother past Sonya, she bowed to her attentively, politely, and with
a deep bow. Sonya blushed, bowed awkwardly and fearfully, some-thing like

The painful sensation reflected in her face, as if the courtesy and attention of Avdotya Romanovna were burdensome and agonizing to her.

— Dunya, farewell! — cried Raskolnikov already in the crowd, — give me your hand too!

— But I was giving it, you forgot? — answered Dunya, affectionately and awkwardly turning to him.

— Well, give it again!

And he tightly squeezed her fingers. Dunya smiled at him, blushed, quickly pulled her hand away and went behind her mother, also somehow happy.

— Well, that’s splendid! — he said to Sonya, returning to himself and clearly looking at her, — may the Lord repose the dead, and may the living continue to live! Is that so? Is that so? Is it?

Sonya looked with surprise at his suddenly enlightened face; he looked at her intently for a few moments in silence: the whole story about the deceased father had suddenly run through his mind in that minute…

— Oh, Dunya! — she spoke immediately, — Pulcheria Alexandrovna, as soon as they stepped out into the street, — see, now she herself is glad that we left: it’s easier somehow. Did I not think yesterday, in the carriage, that I would even rejoice at this!

— I’m telling you again, mother, he is still very ill. Can you not see it? Perhaps, suffering for us, he upset himself. We must be lenient and much, much can be forgiven.

— But you were not lenient at all! — Pulcheria Alexandrovna interrupted hotly and jealously at once. — You know, Dunya, I looked at you both, such a perfect portrait of him, not so much by his face, but by his soul: you both

Melancholics, both gloomy and irritable, both arrogant and both magnanimous… Because it cannot be that he was an egoist, Duniechka? And as I think about what we will have this evening, my whole heart is taken away!

— Do not worry, mother, it will be what it should be.

— Duniechka! Just think about it, what a position we are now in! Well, if Peter Petrovich refuses? — Poor Pulcheria Alexandrovna blurted out carelessly.

— What is he worth after that! — Duniechka retorted sharply and with disdain.

— We did well that we left now, — Pulcheria Alexandrovna hurried on, interrupting, — he is rushing somewhere for a reason: let him walk, let him breathe the air… it’s stifling for him… and where is the air to breathe here? Here, like in rooms without windows. Lord, what a city! — Wait, step aside, they are bringing something! Because they carried the piano, right… how they push! I am also very afraid of this girl…

— What girl, mother?

— That’s Sofiya Semenovna, who was here…

— What about her?

— I have a premonition, Dunya. Well, believe it or not, as she entered, I immediately thought that here is the main one sitting…

— She doesn’t sit at all! — Duniechka exclaimed with annoyance. — And what are you with your premonitions, mother! He only got to know her yesterday, and now, as she entered, he doesn’t recognize her.

— Well, you’ll see! — Pulcheria Alexandrovna exclaimed, — she is disconcerting me, you’ll see, you’ll see! And I was so frightened: she looks at me, looks, her eyes are like that, I could barely sit in the chair

She sat down, remember, how she started to recommend? And it’s strange to me: Peter Petrovich writes about her so, and he recommends her to us, and even to you! So, it’s important to him.

— What if she writes something! She’s talking about us too, and she’s written about us, haven’t they forgotten?
And I’m sure she’s… beautiful, and all this is nonsense!

— May she have it!

— And Peter Petrovich is a nasty gossip, — suddenly interrupted Dunyasha.

Pulcheria Alexandrovna clung to herself. The conversation was interrupted.

— Here’s what, here’s what concern I have with you… — said Raskolnikov,
leading Razumikhin to the window…

— I’ll tell Katya Ivanovna when you come… — she hurried,
saying goodbye in order to leave.

— Now, Sofya Semonovna, we have no secrets, you don’t interfere… I would like to say a few more words to you… Here’s what, — he suddenly turned to Razumikhin, not finishing the thought, abruptly cutting it off. — You know this… how is his name?…
Porfiry Petrovich?

— Of course! Relative. And what’s the matter? — added the other with an explosion of curiosity.

— Because he now leads this… well, here’s the murder… well, you were talking about it yesterday… does it lead?

— Yes… well? — Razumikhin suddenly widened his eyes.

— He was asking about the plant-throwers, and I also have things hidden, yes, sister’s ring, which she gave me as a memory when I left here, and father’s silver watches. They cost five or six rubles, but they are dear to me, a memory. So what am I to do now? I don’t want things to be stolen, especially the watches. I was trembling recently that mother would ask to look at them when

About Dunyashka’s watches, they were talking. The only thing that survived after father.
She will get sick if they disappear! Women! That’s how we should do it, teach me!
I know that one should report to the authorities. But wouldn’t it be better for Porfiry, after all? What do you think? We should deal with this quickly. You’ll see she’ll ask mother before noon!

— Not at all to the authorities and definitely to Porfiry! — shouted Razumikhin in some extraordinary excitement. — Well, how glad I am! What’s the matter, let’s go now, two steps, probably we’ll catch them!

— Perhaps… let’s go…

— And he will be very, very, very, very happy to meet you! I have told him a lot about you, at different times… And yesterday I told him. Let’s go!.. Did you know old woman? Indeed!.. It’s wonderful how it turned out!.. Ah, Sonya Ivanovna…

— Sonya Ivanovna, — corrected Raskolnikov. — Sonya Ivanovna, she is my friend, Razumikhin, and he is a good man…

— If you now need to go… — began Sonya, not even looking at Razumikhin, and this made her even more embarrassed.

— Let’s go! — decided Raskolnikov, — I will visit you today, Sonya Ivanovna, just tell me where you live?

He didn’t get confused, it was as if he was in a hurry and avoiding her gaze. Sonya gave her address and blushed at the same time. They all went out together.

— Don’t you lock up? — asked Razumikhin, descending the stairs behind them.

— Never!… However, I’ve wanted to buy a lock for two years now, — he added carelessly. — Happy people are those who don’t need to lock up? — he said, laughing, to Sonya.

The gates were being struck on the street.

— Are you going to the right, Sofia Semenovna? By the way: how did you find me? — he asked, as if wanting to say something else entirely to her. He wanted to keep looking into her quiet, clear eyes, and somehow it didn’t work out for him…

— Yes, you told Polechka the address yesterday.

— Polechka? Ah yes… Polechka! This is… a small… is she your sister? Did I give her the address?

— Yes, don’t you remember?

— No… I remember…

— And I heard about you from the deceased at the time too… Just didn’t know your surname then, and he himself didn’t know… Now she’s come… and how did she find out your surname yesterday? Then she asked today: where does Mr. Raskolnikov live here?… And she didn’t know that you also live among the tenants… Goodbye-bye… I’m Katerina Ivanovna…

She was terribly glad that she had finally left; she walked dazed, hurrying, so as to leave them out of sight as quickly as possible, to quickly pass these twenty steps to the right onto the street and be left alone, and while walking, hurrying, not looking at anyone, not noticing anything, thinking, remembering, pondering every word spoken, every circumstance. Never before had she felt anything like it. An entirely new world had descended into her soul, unknown and vaguely. She suddenly remembered that Raskolnikov himself wanted to come to her today, maybe this morning, maybe now!

— Only not today, please, not today! — she murmured with a start, as if pleading with someone, like a child in fright. — Oh Lord! To me… into this room… he will see… Oh Lord!

And, of course, she could not have noticed one unfamiliar gentleman watching her at this moment, diligently following her and accompanying her step by step. He had been following her since her exit from the gates. At that moment, when all three of them, Razumikhin, Raskolnikov, and she, stopped for two words on the pavement, this passerby, passing them, suddenly seemed to shudder, unintentionally catching Sonya’s words: “and asked: Mr. Raskolnikov where does he live?” He quickly, but attentively, looked at all three of them, especially at Raskolnikov, to whom Sonya was addressing; then he looked at the house and noticed it. All this was done in an instant, on the move, and the passerby, trying not to show even the slightest appearance, continued on, slowing his pace and as if waiting. He was waiting for Sonya; he saw that they were saying goodbye and that Sonya was going somewhere to herself.

“So where is she going? I’ve seen this face—” he thought, recalling Sonya’s face— “I must find out.”

Reaching the corner, he crossed to the opposite side of the street, turned around and saw that Sonya was already following him, along the same road, and not noticing anything. Reaching the corner, she turned into the same street. He followed her, not taking his eyes off her from the opposite pavement; after walking fifty paces, he crossed again to the side where Sonya was walking, caught up with her and followed her, remaining five steps away.

He was a man of about fifty years old, tall, stout, with broad and sloping shoulders, which gave him a slightly stooped appearance.

He was dapperly and comfortably dressed and looked at the haughty gentleman. In his hands was a beautiful cane, with which he tapped, with each step, along the pavement, and his hands were in fresh gloves. His wide, pinched face was quite pleasing, and his complexion was fresh, not Petersburg-like. His hair, still very thick, was altogether fair-haired and slightly receding, and his wide, thick beard, hanging down like a spade, was even lighter than the hair of his head. His eyes were blue and looked coldly and thoughtfully; his lips were red. In general, he was a man well-preserved and seemed much younger than his years.

When Sonya stepped onto the canal, they found themselves two together on the pavement. Observing her, he managed to notice her thoughtfulness and absentmindedness. Having reached his house, Sonya turned into the gates, he followed after her and seemed somewhat surprised. Entering the courtyard, she turned to the right, into the corner where the staircase to her apartment was. “Well!” – muttered the unfamiliar gentleman and began to climb after her along the steps. It was only then that Sonya noticed him. She went up to the third floor, turned into the gallery and rang the ninth number, on the doors of which was written in chalk: “Kapernaumov seamstress.” “Well!” – he repeated again, surprised by the strange coincidence, and rang the eighth number nearby. Both doors were six steps from each other.

— You are at Kapernaumov’s! – he said, looking at Sonya and laughing. – He sewed my waistcoat for me yesterday. And I am here, next to you, at Madame Resslich, Gertrud Karlovna. How inconvenient it was!

Sonya looked at him attentively.

— The neighbors, — he continued in a particularly cheerful way. — I’ve only been in the city for the third day. Well, goodbye.

Sonia didn’t reply; the door opened, and she slipped into her own room. She felt ashamed for some reason, as if she had become timid…

Razumikhin, on his way to Porfiry, was in a particularly excited state.

— It’s good, brother, — he repeated several times, — and I’m glad! I’m glad!

— “What are you glad about?” — Raskolnikov thought to himself.

— I didn’t even know that you were also visiting her before she died. And… and… how long ago was that? That is, how long had you been with her?

— “What a naive fool!”

— When…? — Razumikhin paused, remembering, — three days before her death, I was there, I think. However, I’m not going to buy things back now… — he snatched up things with a certain hurried and special care, — because I only have a ruble in silver again… because of that cursed delusion yesterday!

About the delusion he spoke with particular emphasis.

— Yes, yes, yes, — Razumikhin hastily and seemingly without understanding responded, — that’s why you were partially struck by it… you know, you were even mentioning rings and chains in your delirium! Yes, yes… It’s clear now.

— “There she is! They’ve let this thought spread among them! This man is going to be crucified for me, and he’s very glad that it’s been explained why I was mentioning rings in my delirium! They’ve all accepted this!”

— Will we catch him? — he asked aloud.

— Let’s catch him, let’s catch him—Ruzimin was in a hurry. —This is a fine guy, you’ll see! A bit clumsy, I mean he’s a worldly man, but I’m talking clumsy in a different sense. The boy is smart, very smart, not stupid at all, just has a peculiar way of thinking… Suspicious, a skeptic, a cynic… he likes to bluff, I mean not to bluff, but to deceive… Well, and he knows his business, he knows—He did one thing, from last year, where he found out about an investigation into an attempted murder, in which almost all the traces were lost! He really, really, really wants to get to know you!

— Why on earth would that be?

— I mean, not that… you see, lately, since you got sick, I’ve often and much talked about you… Well, he listened… and when he found out that you can’t finish your law studies, due to circumstances, he said: “What a pity!” I concluded… I mean, all this together, it’s not one thing; yesterday, Zameotov… See, Rodia, I told you something yesterday in a drunken state, as we were walking home… so I, brother, fear that you won’t exaggerate, you see…

— What is it? Why do they think I’m crazy? Yes, maybe it’s true.

He smiled grimly.

— Yes… yes… I mean, damn it, no!… Well, yes, everything I said (and right away, too), it was nonsense and from a hangover.

— Why are you apologizing! How annoying it is for me!—Raskolnikov shouted with exaggerated irritability. He, however, pretended a little.

— I know, I know, I understand. Be sure that I understand. It’s embarrassing even to say…

— If it’s embarrassing, then don’t say it!

Both fell silent. Razumikhin was more than delighted, and Raskolnikov felt this with aversion. It was also troubling him that Razumikhin was now speaking about Porfiry.

“One must also sing about Lazarus,” he thought, paling and with a pounding heart, “and it is natural to sing about it naturally. Nothing natural of all would be sung. Nothing would be sung intensely! No, it would be intensely unnatural again… Well, let’s see how it turns out… now… is it good or not good that I am coming? A butterfly flies to a candle. The heart is beating, that’s what’s not good!”

— “In this gray house,” said Razumikhin.

“The most important thing is whether Porfiry knows or doesn’t know that I was in that witch’s apartment yesterday and asked about the blood? One must find this out in a single moment, from the very first step, by looking at his face; and-yes… even if I disappear, I must find out!”

— “Do you know what?” he suddenly turned to Razumikhin with a sly smile, — “I, brother, noticed today that you are in some extraordinary agitation this morning? Really?”

— “In what agitation? Not in any agitation at all,” Razumikhin stammered.

— “No, brother, it’s noticeable. You were sitting on the chair the other day as you never sit, as if on the edge, and you were all seized with convulsions. You jumped up suddenly from nowhere. Sometimes angry, sometimes your face became as sweet as a candy; you even blushed; especially when you were invited to dinner, you were terribly red.

— “I told you nothing; you’re lying! What are you talking about?”

— “You’re such a schoolboy, you’re fooling around!” “Damn it, he’s blushing again!”

— “What a pig you are!”

— You’re just messing around? Romeo! Wait, I’ll repeat this somewhere, ha-ha-ha! Here I’ll make Mama laugh… and still some others…

— Listen, listen, listen, this is serious, this is… What’s the point of this after all, damn it! — Razumikhin completely lost it, freezing with horror. — What will you tell them? I, brother… Ugh, what a pig!

— Just a spring rose! And how does that suit you, if you knew; Romeo ten versts tall! How clean you’ve washed yourself today, your nails have been cleaned, haven’t they? When has this happened? God forgive you, you’ve been anointed! Bend down!

— Pig!!!

Raskolnikov was laughing so much that he seemed unable to restrain himself, so they entered Portiya Petrova’s apartment with laughter. That was exactly what was needed for Raskolnikov: from the rooms one could hear that they had entered laughing and were still chuckling in the hallway.

— Not a word here, or I’ll… smash your brains out! — Razumikhin shouted, grabbing Raskolnikov by the shoulder.

— He had already entered the rooms. He had entered with a look as if he was desperately trying not to burst out laughing. Behind him, with a completely overturned and fierce physiognomy, red as a peony, long-bodied and awkwardly, entered the embarrassed Raskolnikov. His face and his figure were truly funny at this moment and justified Raskolnikov’s laughter. Raskolnikov, still not introduced, bowed to the man standing in the middle of the room and looking questioningly at the host, extended and shook his hand with still visible extraordinary effort to suppress his cheerfulness and at least two or three words to introduce himself. But as soon as he managed to take

Serious look and mumble something – suddenly, almost involuntarily, he glanced again at Razumikhin and here he could no longer bear it: suppressed laughter burst out more uncontrollably than it had been suppressed before. Extraordinary ferocity with which this “hearty” laughter Razumikhin took, gave the whole scene the appearance of the most sincere merriment and, главное, naturalness. Razumikhin, as if deliberately, helped the matter.

“Damn it!” he roared, waving his hand and hitting it against a small round table with a cup of tea standing on it. Everything flew and tinkled.

“Why break the chairs, gentlemen, the treasury will suffer!” cheerfully shouted Porfiry Petrovich.

The scene was presented in this way: Raskolnikov was smirking, forgetting his hand in the host’s hand, but, knowing the measure, he waited for the moments as quickly and naturally as possible to end. Razumikhin, completely confused by the fall of the table and the broken glass, gloomily looked at the shards, spat on them, and sharply turned to the window, where he was facing the audience, with a terribly furrowed face, looking out the window and seeing nothing. Porfiry Petrovich laughed and wanted to laugh, but it was obvious that he needed explanations. In the corner on a chair sat Zameтов, having stood up at the entrance of the guests and standing in waiting, having pushed open his mouth with a smile, but looking at the scene with bewilderment and almost with disbelief, and even with some confusion at Raskolnikov. The unexpected presence of Zameтов startled Raskolnikov.

“This is something to think about!” he thought.

“Please excuse me,” he began, becoming even more confused, - Raskolnikov…

“Pardon me, very pleasant, and it’s pleasant you entered like this… Well, that’s it, and he…”

He doesn’t want to greet, — nodded Porfiry Petrovich to Razumikhin.

— I swear, I don’t know why he got so angry at me. I only said to him that he was like Romeo, and… and proved it, and nothing more, it seems.

— Pig! — retorted Razumikhin, not turning around.

— So he had very serious reasons to get so angry over one word, — laughed Porfiry.

— Well, you! investigator!.. Well, let’s go to hell with everyone! — cut off Razumikhin and suddenly, laughing himself, with a brightened face, as if nothing was the matter, approached Porfiry Petrovich.

— What a mess! All fools; let’s get to the point: here is a friend, Rodion Romanich Raskolnikov, firstly, he has heard about you and wanted to meet you, and secondly, he has a little business with you. Come on! What’s your name?

— “This is something else!” — anxiously thought Raskolnikov.

Zametov seemed slightly embarrassed, but not very.

— You met him yesterday, — he said bluntly.

— So God has saved you from loss: last week he was terribly asking me to recommend you to Porfiry, and you two sniffed around without me… Where is your tobacco?

Porfiry Petrovich was in a homely manner, in a dressing gown, in quite clean underwear and in worn-out shoes. He was a man of thirty-five or so, a little shorter than average, full and even with a little belly, clean-shaven, without mustaches or sideburns, with closely trimmed hair on a large, round head, somehow particularly rounded at the back of the head. His plump, round and slightly snub nose was the color of a sick, dark yellow, but quite lively and even mocking. It

It would even have been benevolent, if not for the expression of the eyes, with some watery, glassy sheen, concealed by almost white, blinking eyelashes, as if winking at someone. The gaze of these eyes somehow strangely did not harmonize with the entire figure, which contained even something feminine, and gave it something much more serious than one could expect at first glance.

Porfiry Petrovich, as soon as he heard that the guest had a “small matter” before him, immediately asked him to sit on the sofa, he himself sat at the other end and stared at the guest, in immediate expectation of the presentation of the case, with that intensified and overly serious attention, which even oppressed and confused him from the first time, especially due to unfamiliarity, and especially if what you are presenting is, in your own opinion, far from proportion to such extraordinarily important attention being given to you. But Raskolnikov, in short and coherent words, clearly and accurately explained his case and was so satisfied that he even had time to examine Porfiry Petrovich well. Porfiry Petrovich never took his eyes off him throughout the time. Rumyantsev, having positioned himself opposite, at the same table, closely and impatiently followed the presentation of the case, intermittently shifting his eyes from one to the other and back, which was already a little beyond measure.

“Fool!” he muttered to himself.

“You should file a report with the police,” Porfiry replied, with the most businesslike appearance, “about, you know, that, having learned about such an incident, that is, this murder, you ask the investigator assigned to the case to inform you that such things belong to you and that you wish

They should buy it back… or there… but you, in fact, will write to you.

— That’s the thing, that I, at this very moment, — as much as possible — have embarrassed myself, Raskolnikov, — not entirely with money… and even not for such a trifle can I… I, see, would now only like to state that these things are mine, but that when the money will be…

— It’s the same thing, — replied Porfiry Petrovich, coldly accepting explanations about finances, — and in fact, you can write to me directly, if you wish, in the same sense that, knowing about it and announcing about such things, I ask you…

— You, brother, it seems you are mocking me? — he turned to him, with
artfully displayed irritation. — I agree that, perhaps, I am too
concerned about this rubbish, at your eyes; but one cannot consider me
for this a egoist, nor greedy, and, at my eyes, these two trifling
things may be quite not rubbish. I have already told you now, that these
silver watches, worth little, are the only thing that remained after
father. Laugh at me, but my mother came, — he turned suddenly to
Porfiry, — and if she had known, — he quickly turned back to
Razumikhin, trying especially so that his voice would tremble, — that
these watches were lost, then, I swear, she would be in despair!
Women!

— It’s not at all! I am not in that sense! I am completely
opposite! — shouted the distressed Razumikhin.

— Is it good? Is it natural? Has he exaggerated? — Razumikhin
trembled to himself. — Why did he say: “women”?

— Did your mother come to you? — inquired Porfiry Petrovich
for some reason.

— Yes.

— When was this-s?

— Yesterday evening.

Porfiry remained silent, as if pondering.

— These things could not have disappeared in any case, — he calmly
and coldly continued. — Because I have been waiting for you here for
a long time.

And as if nothing had happened, he carefully offered
Razumikhin’s ashtray, mercilessly crumpling a cigarette onto the
carpet. Razumikhin shuddered, but Porfiry as if did not even look,
still concerned about Razumikhin’s cigarette.

— What-o? Waited! Did you know that he had put it up? — shouted
Razumikhin.

Porfiry Petrovich directly addressed Raskolnikov:

— Your two things, the ring and the watch, were wrapped up under one piece of paper,
and your name was clearly written on the paper with a pencil, as well as the number of the month
when she received them from you…

— How did you notice this so easily? — Raskolnikov awkwardly smirked,
especially trying to look him directly in the eyes; but he couldn’t resist and suddenly
added: — I noticed this because, probably, there were very many bookkeepers… so it would be difficult for you to remember all of them… And you, on the contrary,
remember them all so clearly, and… and…

“Foolish! Weak! Why did I add this!”

— And almost all the bookkeepers are now known, so you were only one and
did not deign to come, — Porfiry replied with a slightly noticeable shade of mockery.

— I wasn’t quite well.

— And I heard about this. I heard even that there were very upset about something.
You are still pale?

— Not at all pale… on the contrary, I am perfectly healthy! — Raskolnikov cut off roughly and angrily, suddenly changing his tone. Anger boiled within him, and he couldn’t suppress it. “And I’ll talk about it in anger!” — it flashed through him again. — And why are they tormenting me!..”

— You weren’t quite well! — Ruzhinikhin snatched up. — He’s been making up stories! Until yesterday he was almost without memory, rambling… Well, you believe, Porfiry, he himself almost stumbled on his feet, and only we, I and Zosim, turned away yesterday — he dressed and quietly fled and played around somewhere until almost midnight, and this in perfect, I

You will скажу, бреду, можешь ты это представить! Замечательнейший случай!

— И неужели в совершеннейшем бреду? Скажите пожалуйста! — с каким-то
бабьим жестом покачал головою Порфирий.

— Э, вздор! Не верьте! А впрочем, ведь вы и без того не верите! -
слишком уж со зла сорвалось у Раскольникова. Но Порфирий Петрович как будто
не расслышал этих странных слов.

— Да как же мог ты выйти, коли не в бреду? — разгорячился вдруг
Разумихин. — Зачем вышел? Для чего?.. И почему именно тайком? Ну был ли в
тебе тогда здравый смысл? Теперь, когда вся опасность прошла, я уж прямо
тебе говорю!

— Надоели они мне очень вчера, — обратился вдруг Раскольников к
Порфирию с нахально-вызывающею усмешкой, — я и убежал от них квартиру
нанять, чтоб они меня не сыскали, и денег кучу с собой захватил. Вон
господин Заметов видел деньги-то. А что, господин Заметов, умен я был вчера
или в бреду, разрешите-ка спор?

Он бы, кажется, так и задушил в эту минуту Заметова. Слишком уж взгляд
его и молчание ему не нравились.

— По-моему, вы говорили весьма разумно-с и даже хитро-с, только
раздражительны были уж слишком, — сухо заявил Заметов.

— А сегодня сказывал мне Никодим Фомич, — ввернул Порфирий Петрович, -
что встретил вас вчера, уж очень поздно, в квартире одного, раздавленного
лошадьми, чиновника…

— Ну вот хоть бы этот чиновник! — подхватил Разумихин, — ну, не
сумасшедший ли был ты у чиновника? Последние деньги на похороны вдове отдал!

Ну, захотел помочь — дай пятнадцать, дай двадцать, ну да хоть три целковых себе оставь, а то все двадцать пять так и отвалил!

— А может, я где-нибудь клад нашел, а ты не знаешь? Вот я вчера и расщедрился… Вон господин Заметов знает, что я клад нашел!.. Вы извините, пожалуйста, — обратился он со вздрагивающими губами к Порфирию, — что мы вас пустяшным таким перебором полчаса беспокоим. Надоели ведь, а?

Is that just my impression? What if it’s a mirage, and I’m wrong about everything, out of inexperience I’m angry, unable to endure this underhanded role? Maybe it’s all without intention? All their words are ordinary, but something is in them… All this can always be said, but something is. Why did he say directly “about her”? Why did Zavetov add that I was speaking cunningly? Why are they speaking in that tone? Yes… tone… Rumykhin immediately sat down, why doesn’t he seem to notice anything? That innocent fool never notices anything! Again, a fever!.. Porphyry winked at me recently, or didn’t he? True, nonsense; why would he wink? Nerves, perhaps, want to irritate me or tease me? Or is it all a mirage, or do they know!.. Even Zavetov is bold… Is Zavetov being bold? Zavetov changed his mind overnight. And I felt that he would. He’s here like his own, but it’s the first time for him. Porphyry doesn’t consider him a guest, he sits with him as a back man. They’ve sniffed at each other! Certainly, they’ve sniffed at me because of me!.. Certainly, they’ve been talking about us!.. Do they know about the apartment? Quickly, let’s find out!.. When I said I would rent an apartment yesterday, he missed it, didn’t raise an eyebrow… And I cleverly inserted the apartment: it will be useful later!.. In a delirium, they said!.. Ha-ha-ha! He knows the whole evening of yesterday! He didn’t know about the mother’s arrival!.. The witch wrote down the number in pencil!.. You’re lying, I won’t let myself be deceived! Because these are not yet facts, it’s only a mirage! Let’s have some facts! And the apartment is not a fact, it’s a delusion; I know what to say to them… Do they know about the apartment? I won’t leave without finding out! Why did I come? Now I’m angry.

так это, пожалуй, и факт! Фу, как я раздражителен! А может, и хорошо; болезненная роль… Он меня ощупывает. Сбивать будет. Зачем я пришел?

Все это, как молния, пронеслось в его голове.

Порфирий Петрович мигом воротился. Он вдруг как-то повеселел.

— У меня, брат, со вчерашнего твоего голова… Да и весь я как-то развинтился, — начал он совсем другим тоном, смеясь, к Разумихину.

— А что, интересно было? Я ведь вас вчера на самом интересном пункте бросил? Кто победил?

— Да никто, разумеется. На вековечные вопросы съехали, на воздусех парили.

— Вообрази, Родя, на что вчера съехали: есть или нет преступление? Говорил, что до чертиков доврались!

— Что ж удивительного? Обыкновенный социальный вопрос, — рассеяно ответил Раскольников.

— Вопрос был не так формулирован, — заметил Порфирий.

— Не совсем так, это правда, — тотчас же согласился Разумихин, торопясь и разгорячаясь по обыкновению. — Видишь, Родион: слушай и скажи свое мнение. Я хочу. Я из кожи лез вчера с ними и тебя поджидал; я и им про тебя говорил, что придешь… Началось с воззрения социалистов. Известно воззрение: преступление есть протест против ненормальности социального устройства — и только, и ничего больше, и никаких причин больше не допускается, — и ничего!..

— Вот и соврал! — крикнул Порфирий Петрович. Он видимо оживлялся и поминутно смеялся, смотря на Разумихина, чем еще более поджигал его.

— Н-ничего не допускается! — с жаром перебил Разумихин, — не вру!.. Я тебе книжки ихние покажу: все у них потому, что «среда заела», — и ничего

More! Favorite phrase! From here directly, that if society is arranged normally, then immediately and all crimes will disappear, because there will be nothing for which to protest, and everyone will become righteous in a single moment. Nature does not take into account nature, nature is expelled, nature does not rely on! They do not have humanity, having developed historically, living way to the end, will turn itself finally into a normal society, but, on the contrary, a social system, having emerged from some mathematical head, will immediately arrange all humanity and in a single moment will make it righteous and sinless, before any living process, without any historical and living path! That is why they so instinctively and do not love history: “one only foolishness explains one only absurdity” — and all one only foolishness! That is why they so much do not love the living process of life: one does not need a living soul! A living soul of life will demand, a living soul will not obey mechanics, a living soul is suspicious, a living soul is retrograde! And here it goes, as if it were a corpse, it can be made of rubber, — but it is not living, it is not free, it is slavish! It will not rebel! And as a result, it turns out that everyone is reduced to one only bricklaying and to the arrangement of corridors and rooms in a phalanster! The phalanster is ready, but your nature is not yet ready for the phalanster, it wants life, the living process has not yet been completed, too early to the cemetery! One logic cannot jump over nature! Logic will predict three cases, and their million! Cut off the whole million and reduce everything to one question about comfort! The easiest solution to the problem! Tempting, clear, and you do not need to think! The whole life secret fits on two printed sheets!

— And here it burst through, banging! You must hold hands, — laughed
Porfiry. — Imagine, — he turned to Raskolnikov, — just as yesterday
evening, in one room, in six voices, and still with a shot of vodka
preliminarily, — can you imagine it? No, brother, you are lying: “среда”
means much in the crime; I will confirm this to you.

— And I know myself that much, but you say this: a fifty-year-old man dishonors
a ten-year-old girl, — was “среда,” as it were, forcing him to do this?

— What’s the matter, it’s, in strict terms, perhaps, that it was “среда,” — Porfiry noted with surprising
importance, — the crime against the girl is very and very even
explainable by “среда.”

Razumikhin almost came to a frenzy.

— Well, if you want, I’ll show you now, — he roared, — that your white eyelashes are only because there are thirty-five sazhen
heights in Ivan the Great, and I’ll clearly, precisely, progressively and even with a liberal shade?
I’m taking the risk! Well, if you want, a bet!

— I accept! Let’s listen to how he’ll explain it!

— But he’s pretending, damn it! — Raskolnikov shouted, jumped up and
waved his hand. — It’s pointless to talk to you! Because he’s doing all this deliberately, you don’t yet know him, Rodion! And yesterday they took his side, only to deceive everyone. And what he said yesterday, God! And they were so happy for him!..
He endured it for two weeks like that. Last year he convinced us for something that he was going to become a monk: he stood firm for two months! Recently he started to assure us that he was getting married, that everything was ready for the wedding. He even sewed a new dress. We

They had already begun to congratulate him. There was neither a bride, nor anything else: it was all an illusion!

— You even lied! I sewed a dress before. It came to my head, because of the new dress, to inflate you all.

— Are you really such a pretender? — Raskolnikov asked carelessly.

— Didn’t you think there wasn’t? Wait, I’ll take you with me — ha-ha-ha! No, see, I’ll tell you the whole truth. Regarding all these questions, crimes, circles, girls, it now occurred to me, — but in any case, — and always interested me, — one of your articles: “On Crime”… or how it was called, I forgot the name, don’t remember. I had the pleasure of reading it two months ago in “The Periodic Word.”

— My article? In “The Periodic Word”? — Raskolnikov asked with surprise, — I wrote it six months ago, when I left the university, regarding one book, one article, but I deleted it then into the newspaper “The Weekly Word,” and not into “The Periodic Word.”

— And it appeared in “The Periodic Word.”

— Yes, “The Weekly Word” ceased to exist, so they didn’t print it then…

— That’s true-s; but, ceasing to exist, “The Weekly Word” merged with “The Periodic Word,” and therefore your article, two months ago, appeared in “The Periodic Word.” And you didn’t know?

Raskolnikov really didn’t know anything.

— Forgive me, but you could ask them money for the article! What, however, do you have such a character! You live so secluded that things directly concerning you are not known to you. This is a fact-s.

— Bravo, Rodion! And I didn’t know either! — Razumikhin shouted. — Today, in

